o.org</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">NCVO convenes the Public Service Delivery Network, a group of 2500 organisations that have an interest in public service delivery. NCVO also convenes a Spec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ial Interest Group (SIG) of sub</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contractor organisations involved in the Work Programme, an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d a Payment-by-Results working group.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This written submission is intended to supplement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oral </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evidence given by NCVO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at the Justice Committee evidence session on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Crime Reduction policies: a coordinated approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">?’ on 12 November 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was focused on the Government’s Transforming Rehabilitation programme. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In this submission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we focus on the impact that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the intended structure of the Transforming Rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contracts and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the proposed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">payment mechanism will have on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">voluntary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> commu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nity and social enterprise (VCSE)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sector and on rehabilitation outcomes.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">draw on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">findings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from a recent report from NCVO and Bates Wells Braithwaite</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (BWB)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which analyses a sample of Payment by Results</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (PbR)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contracts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> held </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by VCSE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> providers.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">refer to our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">feedback </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we have previously given to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Ministry of Justice’s (MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) proposed payment mechanism for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Transforming Rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contracts.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> VCSE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, many involving dedicated volunteers,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> can make all the difference to the lives of people leaving prison and help</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reduce reoffending. G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iven the right conditions, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the VCSE sector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can add significant value to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Transforming Rehabili</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a number</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of concerns</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> about the impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the proposed contract structure and payment model will have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on the VCSE sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s involvement in this programme, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as well as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on rehabilitation outcomes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In this summary, we would like to raise some key points before the Committee which are explained further throughout this response. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.22pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are concerned that there will be a lack of spe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nding on rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> within these contracts, at least within the first few years of delivery. This is due to the fact that Tier 1 providers will be facing high reconfiguration costs as well as expectations of financial efficiencies, and will therefore be focused </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on delivering</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> core</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> court mandated services. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.22pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In order to ensure that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> more prolifi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">c offenders are not ‘parked’ by providers, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he way in which reductions in reoffending are measured must reward reductions in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">frequency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of reoffending</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> across offender cohorts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 49.22pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Pa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ym</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ent by Results (PbR) models can be extremely challenging for small and medium </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sized </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">organisations including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">those from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VCSE s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The use of PbR throughout supply chains</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in ‘Transforming Rehabilitation’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will restrict the diversity o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f the market, an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d therefore a mix of funding mechanism</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should be used by Tier 1 providers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Investment and spend on rehabilitation services</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are concerned that there will be a lack of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">investment in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rehabilitation within these contracts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The payments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> spl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a monthly Fee for Service (FFS) payment which will pay for th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e court mandated services, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Payment by Results (PbR)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> payments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which will pay for reduced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reoffending. It is possible that Tier 1 providers will focus on maximising their safe margins by adjust</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing their operating costs to increase their gains from the FFS payment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with no additional investment being made into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the PbR element of the contract.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is compounded by the fact that there will be high reconfigurations costs for the Tier 1 providers t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aking on these contracts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, coupled with high expectations from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the financial efficiencies which should be made. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For Tier 1 providers, assembling complex and diverse supply chains to deliver additional rehabilitation services would be e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">xpensive. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t is likely that Tier 1 providers will focus instead on stabilising their core delivery model, at least for the first few years of the contract. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some VCSE organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are already reporting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> having their current contracts with Probation Trusts ended and are concerned about a lack of clarity around whether the Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) will be renewing or continuing contracts when they are established in April. This transition </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">period is an uncertain time for many VCSE organisations, and we are concerned about the impact this funding instability will have on the quality of rehabilitation outcomes. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are concerned about the impact of this on the sustainability of VCSE organisat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ions who work with offenders to help them desist from crime; the lack of funding to these organisations will disrupt the market’s access to speciali</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">st staff who are experienced in working with the most entrenched an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> prolific offenders. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The impact the Pb</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">R model has on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">the way providers work with service users</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">:</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Paying providers for the results which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they achieve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">carries the inherent risk that providers may</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">choose to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">work with those providers who are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">easier to achieve results with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in order</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to maximise their profits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and minimise the financial risks of not delivering results</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Using </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a well-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">designed payment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> tariff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> can disincentive this behaviour, however we have found from our recent review that too often payments are designed without consultat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ion with the market, and with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">out</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> an understanding of how the model might prompt perverse incentives.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We also know from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Work Programme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that ‘creaming and parking’ can occur when payment mechanisms are badly designed: this is when providers focus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on service users closest to the job market at the expense of  those who may require more complex or sustained interventions to get</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> them into work</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are concerned that the proposed payment mechanism for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">using </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PbR in T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ransforming </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contains</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">similar </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">risk that the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hardest to reach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will be parked</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It should be noted that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">odel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> put out by the MoJ in June</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is a ‘Straw Man’</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and not a finalised version, and the MoJ published a summary of possible changes in October. </span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One of our key conce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rns has been the way in which the model proposes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">measur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reductions in reoffending</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which will be paid for.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As currently proposed, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">targets must be met for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">complete desistence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> across a cohort of offenders before any payments for reducing the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">frequency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of reoffending will be made.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This is referred to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as the ‘binary hurdle.’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> We are concerned t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">his will prompt the ‘parking’ of the most prolific offenders, those considered the most difficul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t to achieve results with, as these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> results are demonstrate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d by a decline in the f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">requency of their reoffending. P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">roviders </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">working with offenders who require sustained and complex interventions throughout their journey towards reform will not be sufficiently funded.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The latest update from the MoJ shows that the G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overnment is considering the most appro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">priate way to address the issue of ‘parking’ certain offenders.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is a promising indication; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">too often in designing PbR models, the commissioner proceeds without this kind of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">market </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">engagement, and ends up having </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to restructure a flawed contract whilst it is operational</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Several measures are being considered </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by the MoJ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">about how best to incentiv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e working with prolific offenders:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> NCVO would strongly recommend the removal of the binary hurdle. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The impact of PbR </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">on the voluntary sector. </span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In NCVO and BWB’s recent review of PbR contracts and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">experiences of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> VCSE providers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> delivering them, we found that the financial requirements of PbR, in terms of the working capital and cash flow needed to fund payment in arrea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rs, have meant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> providers have had to: subsidise their PbR work with other income from other sources; limit the amount of other services they can deliver; and seek loans to cover payment delays.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of many VCSE subcontractors in the Work </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Programme also demonstrates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the financial risks in PbR contracts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> can be unsustainable. An </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">NCVO survey of VCSE experience of the Work Programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> found that 70 of respondents feared their contracts would not be viable for the full term, and nearly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> half of the respondents were subsidising their service delivery with their own reserves.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The financial terms of PbR contracts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> shutting VCSE organisations out of public services delivery. A Compact Voice survey </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(2013)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> found that 42% of VCSE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">responde</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nts believe that the financial risks and capital requirements involved in PbR ‘completely’ limit their ability to compete</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for contracts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The use of PbR in T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ransforming Rehabilitation is likely to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have a similar impact on the VCSE sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s ability to bid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for and deliver these contracts. Certainly at a Tier 1 level, none but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the largest VCSE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> organisations are going to be able to bid for contracts, although </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it should be noted too that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this is largely du</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e to the size of the contracts.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At Tier 2 and 3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> level, it is not yet certain how </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">much PbR will be flowed down and how risk with be allocated. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our recent analysis with BWB has highlighted a number of incidences of poor practice in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">way risk is placed in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sub</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contracts. One example is where the sub</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ontract contained a clause which stipul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ated that the providers would not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be paid until the P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rime had been paid by the commissioner</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This would mean that,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> regardless of whether the provider had achieve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the outcomes which they were contracted to achieve, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">heir pa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">yment would be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> dependent on a number of variables which they had no influence over.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This is clearly an inappropriate allocation of risk. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The MoJ are intending t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o develop industry standard sub-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contracts, and one of their market stewardship principles which Tier 1 providers will be expected to adhere to will be the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">appropriate management of risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  However, without seeing the detail, it is difficult to know whether these measures will robustly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ensure the fair treatment of the supply chain. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are aware that the MoJ are intending to put in place mechanisms in the main </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contracts which ease cash flow difficulties.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is essential that where the Tier 1 provider is benefiting from measures which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">address some of the financial risk of PbR, this reduction in risk is reflected throughout the supply chain.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In many cases it will simply not be appropriate for the Tier 1 providers to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">subcontract</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> us</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing PbR. In order to sustain a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> plural market, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hich</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the ability to deliver quality outcomes across demographics and localities, Tier 1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">providers must be encouraged by MoJ to use a mix of funding mechanisms incl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uding grants and fee for service contracts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Market stewardship proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> and supply chain st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">andards</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The MoJ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is taking</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> steps to improve on previous models of market stewardship and supply chain management. The Merlin Standard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> used by DWP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, for example, although containing some important prin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ciples, has not sufficiently protected</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">subcontract</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Work Programme. Bad practice in the Work Programme not addressed by Merlin </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Standard include: the use of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> VCSE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">providers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as ‘bid candy’ by Prime providers who didn’t have any intention of subcontracting to them; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the lack of referrals to voluntary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sector providers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> who had expected and planned for a certain level of income.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> In addition to this, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Merlin Standard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is a retrospective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evaluation, and not a sufficient starting point for building supply chain relationships. The assessment process al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">so allowed Primes to choose which subcontractors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were interviewed by the a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ssessors, and there was not a sufficient and robust enough complaints process.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At this stage, the MoJ’s market stewardship principles are looking likely to make i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mprovements in su</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pply chain standards. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, we are interested to see the detail of how the Market Stewardship principles are integrated into the contract management processes as well as the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> industry standard sub</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contracts before we can judge their likely effectiveness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> BWB and NCVO, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">October </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">2013. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Payment by results contracts: a legal analysis of terms and process</span><span style="font-family:Calib